The prepared NF membranes morphologies including surface and cross-section were visualized by SEM and AFM (Figs. 6 and 7

                           ). PA-1 shows a typical morphology of interfacial polymerization NF membranes, and some nodular structures appeared on the membrane surface [48]. After incorporation of CQD/TiO2 NPs, the PA-(2–5) exhibits more grainy membrane morphologies, showcasing rougher surfaces. The cross-sections of PA-1 and PA-4 membranes were shown in Fig. 7. Both membranes exhibited continuous and defect-free selective layers, and the thickness of PA-1 and PA-4 membranes were 112 and 87 nm, respectively. The decrease of thickness in this work implies that the retardation effect of CQD/TiO2 NPs dominates the thickness of selective layers. The negatively charged surface of CQD/TiO2 NPs can absorb a certain amount of PIP, which enlarged the reaction areas and slowed down the diffusion of PIP to the hexane phase, leading to thinner selective layers [45,48,49]. AFM was used to confirm the surface roughness (Fig. 7). When the concentration of CQD/TiO2 NPs was 0.035 wt%, the average roughness R
                           a of PA-4 increased from the initial 8.35 nm to 10.45 nm, which was consistent with the SEM results.
